	(1890,1832,'ENU0151',104,1,'奇幻文學','Fantasy Literature',4104,'','','H',3,56,'',1,'3','N',0,'1','◎限本系修習◎限大三大四修習',0,'','本部樸204',NULL,'五7-9',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,5,50,3,'This course, first of all, orients students into various representative modern fantasy writers (Sade, Hoffmann, Poe, Lovecraft, Wells, Kafka, Le Guin, Gibson, Oates and Gaiman) and its generic characteristics such as metamorphosis, existential and structural uncertainty, alternative spatio-temporal experiences, and so on. Psychoanalytic perspectives are introduced and, later, applied to textual analysis. Reading materials include five short stories and two novels, which cover various sub genres of fantasy (the Gothic, horror, the grotesque, and utopia) and are analytically, critically accessed by way of lectures and discussions with a view to not only psychological but also social and political aspects.',0,24,24,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1891,1833,'ENU0176',104,1,'文學理論導讀','Introduction to Literary Theory',4094,'','','H',3,56,'',0,'3','N',0,'1','◎限本系修習◎限大三大四修習',0,'','本部誠305',NULL,'二6-8',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,3,50,3,'Objectives This course introduces to students various modes of modern theory including Marxism, psychoanalysis, postmodernism and postcolonialism. Besides a comprehensive historical survey of these theories, students will be required to read, discuss, and critique some representative theoretical texts in detail and to develop accurate, critical understanding of such essential concepts as reification, ideological interpellation, the unconscious, the ego-superego-id structure, drive, Panopticon, simulacrum, to name only a few. Some cinematic and literary texts will be analyzed in light of these theoretical concepts.',0,29,29,0,3,0,0,0,0),
	(1892,1834,'ENU0177',104,1,'亞美文學','Asian American Literature',4095,'','','H',3,56,'',0,'3','N',0,'1','◎限本系修習◎限大三大四修習',0,'','本部正302',NULL,'二6-8',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,6,50,3,'This course is designed for story-telling, story-reading, and story-sharing. We\'ll read and discuss stories that have emerged in-between \"Asia\" and \"America\" out of the trans-Pacific flows of people, cultures, politics, and histories since the second half of the nineteenth century. By reading and discussing stories of immigrants, migrants, exiles, travelers, students, cultural mediators, etc., we will understand Asian Americans\' engagement with and intervention into the construction of Asia, America, and the Pacific history and humanities. We\'ll read selections from novels, short stories, poetry, watch films (documentaries and feature-lengths), enjoy music, and think creatively, with our topics of concerns ranging from race, gender, ethnicity, language, identity, human rights, to life politics. In view of the hybrid ethnic and historical constitutions of \"Asian America,\" in the 2013 Fall semester we will study mainly Chinese American and Japanese American stories to make our discussion focused and systematic. Besides, participants are encouraged to reflect on their own experiences of living and learning between Asia and Euro-America as English majors in Taiwan. This course aims to raise participants\' interest and understanding in important issues of cultural exchange, self and other, identity and power, and nation and ethnicity. Participants are encouraged to share their reading and learning experiences. Requirements include group assignments, discussions, presentations, and two short (3-5 pages) response papers. 這是一門讀故事、聽故事、與說故事的課程。我們要以「亞-美」的故事-即亞洲和美洲之間從十九世紀後半期以來流動的人、事、政治、與歷史-為主要研讀材料，看「亞-美」社群（包括移民至美洲的亞裔、在亞洲與美洲之間經商、求學、工作、旅遊的文化仲介者、還有從美洲回到亞洲的跨國遷徙者）如何介入與建構亞洲、美洲，以及跨太平洋的歷史與人文。課程內容包括閱讀小說、詩歌、散文、論文、聽音樂、與觀看影片（包括劇情長片與紀錄片），透過對不同形式亞美文化作品的研讀與討論，思考種族、性別、族群、語言、身份、人權與生命政治等議題。有鑑於亞美涵蓋眾多亞洲國家人民的跨太平洋經驗，為了讓整學期的討論集中與深入，我們在2013年秋季學期會以華裔與日裔的故事為討論重心，另外也鼓勵同學從閱讀亞美文學，進而反思在台灣讀英語系，接觸歐美文學，在不同文化脈絡中找尋自我、建立自身思維主體性的生活與學習經驗。 這一門課希望能帶出同學對文化流動、自我與他者、身份與權力、國家與族群等議題的興趣與理解。非常鼓勵同學參與討論，並分享彼此的閱讀與學習經驗。課程要求包括分組作業、討論、報告、以及兩篇3-5頁針對閱讀內容的回應報告。',0,4,4,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1893,1835,'ENU0199',104,1,'城市文學','Urban Literature',4105,'','','H',3,56,'',1,'3','N',0,'1','◎限本系修習◎限大三大四修習',0,'','本部正303',NULL,'三6-8',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,5,50,3,'This course highlights the interaction between urban space and the representations of urban specificities in the context of postmodern/postcolonial discourses. It is designed to help students better understand such concepts as the city, space, and the flâneur. It is hoped that through a perusal of critical theories and in-depth textual practice, students have a thorough grasp of important issues in urban studies. The course organization will include three interrelated parts. First, we will begin with perusing critical discourses concerning the concept of the city, the configuration of space in the city, and the role the flâneur plays in the formation of urban landscape. Secondly, the course will include a theoretical application of the above discourses to several novels and films. We will discuss the relations among urban narratives, cultural production, and representation. It is hoped that through a training of dialectical thinking, students can understand how the representations of urban lives and cultural production reflect off the heterogeneous spaces overlooked as well as how the urban representation provides a site of ideological wrestling. Thirdly, students are also required to study a set of significant key terms often encountered in urban studies. Equipped with a sound knowledge of urban studies, students are expected to synthesize the three parts and explore the interaction between urban narratives and contemporary cultural products.',0,24,24,0,4,0,0,0,0),
	(1894,1836,'ENU0206',104,1,'語言與大腦','Language and Brain',4074,'','','H',3,56,'',1,'3','N',0,'1','◎限本系修習◎限大三大四修習',0,'','本部正304',NULL,'三7-9',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,5,50,3,'You will learn about how language is represented in the mind and brain, and how it is processed between the ears and the brain, and between the brain and the mouth/hands.',0,45,45,0,1,0,0,1,0),
	(1895,1837,'ENU0219',104,1,'職場英文','English for Occupational Purposes',4093,'','','H',2,56,'',1,'3','N',0,'1','◎限本系修習◎限大三大四修習',0,'','本部正304',NULL,'二9-10',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,0,50,2,'The course is specifically designed for students who plan to start their career in fields including business, international trade, information technology, and journalism and news media. The course provides essential communication skills and real-world content for occupational purpose, introducing topics and issues such as business letters and memos writing, financial vocabulary and knowledge, communication techniques, career in information industry, and global financial crisis. Since the TOEIC test has become increasingly important in many careers in the recent decade, sample materials selected from the test will be incorporated into the course. Authentic materials such as business documents, footages, news stories and reports, files, and recordings are also used to supplement the textbook.',0,19,19,0,4,0,0,0,0),
