	(1939,1588,'ENM2027',104,1,'研究方法與論文寫作','Research Methods and Academic Writing',4121,'','','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'','',0,'','本部教室自排',NULL,'四2-4',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,0,50,3,'This course aims to help students develop the ability to compose a well-organized and well-focused academic essay in English. Its goals are to introduce strategies for the purpose, organization, presentation, development, coherence, and unity of thesis writing. Essential elements in a thesis such as summaries, abstracts, arguments, data commentaries, critiques, etc. will be discussed and practice in writing will be assigned. Whenever appropriate, we will also talk about skills in doing independent academic research in language and linguistics. Students are expected to learn to use library resources and explore various approaches of data collection and analysis. The ultimate purpose is to familiarize students with the steps in doing academic research and help them develop abilities in critical thinking/writing, intellectual reasoning, problem-solving, and collaborative learning.',0,12,12,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1940,1589,'ENM3028',104,1,'研究方法與學術論文寫作（一）','Research Methods and Academic Writing (I)',4122,'','','H',2,57,'',1,'','N',0,'','',0,'','本部教室自排',NULL,'三3-4',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,1,50,2,'The purpose of this course is to help graduate students improve their academic writing in English and provide them an overview of research-related issues. The class will first introduce the language used in academic writing, followed by the different sections commonly seen in a research paper. Students are expected to lead class discussions, give presentations and write parts of a research paper. The class is designed based on the premise of a constructivist approach. Students are expected to learn by actual doing, exploring actively on their own and constructing their individual understanding and knowledge. The class also aims for foster collaboration and discussions. Based on these, lectures are cut down to minimum. Each student will be evaluated by their progress made in this class.',0,15,15,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1941,1590,'ENC1001',104,1,'莎士比亞研討','Studies in Shakespeare',4123,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','本部教室自排',NULL,'三7-9',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,5,50,3,'1. In this course, we are going to study a dozen Shakespearean plays, adaptations, and related scholarly articles. 2. Our major textbook is: Stephen Greenblatt, ed., The Norton Shakespeare, Based on the Oxford Edition. New York: Norton, 1997. 3. A detailed schedule is to be discussed and decided after orientation in the first week. It will normally be announced in the class in the second week of the term.',0,11,11,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1942,1591,'ENC1011',104,1,'二十世紀美國重要作家','Major 20th-Century American Authors',4124,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','本部教室自排',NULL,'三3-5',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,3,50,3,'In Major American Writers of the 20th century, students will study a wide range of fiction from 1930 to the present. The course traces the formal and thematic developments of the novel in this period, focusing on the relationship between writers and readers, the conditions of publishing, innovations in the novel`s form, fiction`s engagement with history, and the changing place of literature in American culture. The reading list includes works by Flannery O`Connor, William Faulkner, Saul Bellow, John Updike, Marilynne Robinson, and Cormac McCarthy, as well as a packet of theoretical and critical readings put together by the instructor.',0,10,10,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1943,1592,'ENC1065',104,1,'十九世紀英國小說','19th-Century English Novel',4125,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','本部教室自排',NULL,'二3-5',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,3,50,3,'本課程有系統地介紹十九世紀英國小說及相關社會、歷史與文化等議題。因為有部分學生可能已修過或將選修「十九世紀英國女作家」，因此本課程以男小說家的作品為主，而以女小說家的作品為輔。由於十九世紀英國小說家曾嘗試不同的小說型式，本課程也將逐一介紹這些不同的小說類型的特色，包括有歷史小說、感性小說、成長小說、哥德式小說、鄉土小說、童話小說、科幻小說、以及冒險與奇幻小說等。最後本課程也將介紹十九世紀與後現代的小說理論，以及小說家與小說作品在十九世紀與二十一世紀受歡迎的程度。本課程期望學生對十九世紀英國小說的發展能有通盤且深入的瞭解。 As the Victorian period is arguably the most complex, rapidly-changing and replete with the myriad of social problems and conflicts, such as gender, education, social welfare, poverty, industrialization, and crime, among others, the Victorian fiction reflects many social dimensions. We hope to explore broadly and also in depth the representative novels of some major writers, such as Charles Dickens, Rudyard Kipling, Sir Arthur Conan Doyle, Wilkie Collins, and Joseph Conrad. This \"Nineteenth-Century Novels\" course hopes to focus particularly on several major issues: British imperialism, London cosmopolitanism, crime and industrialization, urbanity, modernity, the genre of Gothic and Detective Fiction, the transition between Victorianism and Modernism. The issue of transition between Victorianism and Modernism is fascinating. Some perceive Victorian fiction as forerunner of Modern fiction. For instance, Raymond Williams argues, that since industrialization and urbanization feature modernity, the dating of British Modernism should start from the Victorian period. For him, the Victorian period was the beginning of modernism and modernity, and Charles Dickens should be considered as a forerunner of Modernist fiction. Another major modernist writer, Joseph Conrad, often conceived as the father of Modern fiction, with his complex narratives, actually wrote and published some of his early novels in the late nineteenth century, such as Almayer\'s Folly in 1895, An Outcast of the Islands, 1896; \"An Outpost of Progress,\" 1897; and Heart of Darkness, 1899. Hence, we will reconsider the issue when Victorianism ends and when Modernism starts. In the nineteenth century, especially during the Victorian reign, the imperial conflict between China and the British Empire, and two colonial military expeditions to China incurred by the Opium trade play a large part in the period. Hence, one of the major issues we intend to explore in this course is the representation of China and opium in the Victorian fiction, especially in the novels by the Oscar Wilde, Charles Dickens, Wilkie Collins, and Sir Arthur Conan Doyle. We will also explore the issues of London cosmopolitanism, as London being the epicenter of the British Empire. We will investigate the connection between London as the capital of the British Empire and its peripherals and colonies, especially India and China. Opium smoking in London seems to play a significant part in late Victorian writing. Some of the novels by Dickens, Collins and Wilde in our reading list depict the opium dens in London\'s East End, while Kipling\'s stories depict the opium factory in India.',0,7,7,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1944,3324,'ENC1097',104,1,'種族與文化再現','Race and Cultural Representation',4126,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','本部教室自排',NULL,'五2-4',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,5,50,3,'I have many thoughts regarding my teaching philosophy. Some of them can be summarized as follows: I try to give my work as a teacher all the energy, inquisitiveness, enjoyment, commitment , and preparation I can muster. I expect students to work diligently. I will look into the selected texts from an Afrocentric perspective and we will explore the opportunities to study the following authors in the light of a modern philosophy, i.e. Afrocentric methodology developed for the study and analysis of African American discourse. The ten steps I have developed will be utilized in this course to explore the dimensions and contours of a methodological approach to Harlem Renaissance literature and literary genres. My pedagogy depends heavily on dialogue and thus responses to the texts. No student\'s grade has ever suffered because the student disagrees with me. Yet, we must all recognize the difference between intellectual competence and political opinion. Since our subject matter stimulates emotions and challenges the master narrative, we shall work through difficult issues as an enlightened group.',0,17,17,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1945,1594,'ENC2008',104,1,'中英句法比較分析','Comparative Study of Chinese Syntax and English Syntax',4127,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','本部教室自排',NULL,'二6-8',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,2,50,3,'This course is intended to explore the workings of Universal Grammar by comparing the syntax of Chinese and the syntax of English (as well as other languages when necessary). Important topics in syntax will be discussed by covering both classical and up-to-date works. With the goal to enhance the understanding of Universal Grammar, this course will benefit not only students who are interested in syntactic theory, Chinese and English syntax, but also those working on interfaces between syntax and other linguistic areas (such as sentence processing, L1 or L2 acquisition, etc.).',0,5,5,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1946,1595,'ENC2010',104,1,'國語閩南語句法比較分析','Comparartive Study of Mandarin Syntax and Taiwanese Syntax',4128,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','本部教室自排',NULL,'四2-4',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,2,50,3,'This course will focus on the comparison between Mandarin and Southern Min syntax in three major areas: negation and question, word order, and noun phrases. Since it will be couched in Chomsky\'s Principles and Parameters theory (1981), several meetings in the beginning of the course will be devoted into the discussion of the framework and the significance of such an approach for dialectal studies. They will be followed by the discussion of the papers related to the three areas. Students who are not familiar with the theoretical framework are strongly encouraged to prepare themselves by studying it.',0,1,1,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1947,1596,'ENC2012',104,1,'臺灣南島語言語法','Formosan Syntax',4129,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','本部教室自排',NULL,'三3-5',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,0,50,3,'This course offers an introduction to various morphosyntactic phonomena of Formosan languages, focusing on the discussion of such phenomena from a typological perspective.',0,8,8,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1948,1597,'ENC2014',104,1,'語意學研討','Studies in Semantics',4130,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','本部教室自排',NULL,'一2-4',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,3,50,3,'Studies in Syntax is designed as an introduction to contemporary work in syntactic theory. The framework that we will be discussing in class is Chomsky\'s Minimalist Program. By the end of the course, students should be able to understand the main ideas behind the theory (especially with respect to how it differs from its predecessor - Government & Binding) and also to read and analyze Minimalist articles critically. The course is designed as a mixture of lectures, student presentations, and in-class discussions. Please do the readings in a timely manner in order to be able to follow and participate in these discussions. A term paper/squib (8-10 pages, double-spaced) is due at the end of the semester. Students have to choose one or more papers in consultation with the teacher and provide a critical summary, ideally also presenting original data that supports or provides evidence against the analysis in the article.',0,4,4,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1949,1598,'ENC2026',104,1,'社會語言學','Sociolinguistics',4131,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','本部教室自排',NULL,'三7-9',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,0,50,3,'Course Description This course provides an overview of the field of sociolinguistics, the study of language in its social and cultural contexts. It considers variations of language (in a broad sense) and the socio-cultural factors associated with variations. Among the questions posed in the course are these: How and why do speakers select among the range of linguistic varieties in their repertoire, one language or another, standard or vernacular, regional-sounding or not, formal or casual, gendered in one way or another, and so on? How can such variation be accounted for in a theory of language and society? What kind of knowledge is involved in knowing how to participate in conversations, and how do conversational styles differ from group to group? What are the effects of multilingualism and language contact, for speakers, for communities, and for languages? How and why do standard varieties of languages come to be? Throughout the course, we will learn a variety of theoretical and methodological approaches to the investigation of sociolinguistic data. We will also gain first-hand experience in data collection and analysis through project assignments. Students are highly encouraged to apply sociolinguistic theories and findings discussed in class to communities with which they have personal experiences.',0,33,33,0,0,0,0,0,0),
